  "reason_thou": "1. **Understanding the Issue**: The crash occurs in
`OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` when processing an ifunc whose resolver function
(`f1`) contains only an `unreachable` instruction (no return). The code assumes
that after scanning all basic blocks, at least one callee version will have
been collected via `collectVersions`. However, when the resolver has no return
instructions (like `unreachable`), `Callees` remains empty, triggering the
assertion `!Callees.empty()`.\n\n2. **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The debug output
shows the assertion failure at line 2554. The resolver `f1` has a single basic
block terminated by `unreachable`, not a `ReturnInst`. The `any_of` loop
returns false (no block caused `collectVersions` to fail), but `Callees` is
empty because `collectVersions` was never called.\n\n3. **Root Cause
Analysis**: The logic incorrectly assumes that if `any_of` returns false (no
failures), then at least one callee version must have been collected. This is
false when the resolver contains no return instructions at all. Such resolvers
cannot provide callee versions for ifunc resolution and should be skipped, not
asserted.\n\n4. **Proposed Edit Point(s)**: Replace the assertion at line 2554
with a check that skips the ifunc when `Callees` is empty. The assertion should
remain for cases where `collectVersions` was called but returned no versions
due to some error, but we need to handle the \"no return instructions\" case
gracefully.\n\n   Current code:\n   ```cpp\n   assert(!Callees.empty() &&
\"Expecting successful collection of versions\");\n   ```\n\n   Proposed fix:\n
```cpp\n   if (Callees.empty())\n     continue;\n   ```\n\n   This allows the
pass to skip ifuncs whose resolvers don't return any function pointers (e.g.,
`unreachable` resolvers), which is semantically correct\u2014such ifuncs cannot
be statically resolved.\n\n5. **Conclusion**: The fix ensures that
`OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` gracefully skips ifuncs with resolvers that provide
no callee versions, rather than crashing. This matches the pass's intent: only
